<p>There are a lot of misnomers about financially sustainable travel. I gue=
ss it stands to reason: I coined the term, somewhat accidentally at that. S=
ince those early days, it has been used in a variety of contexts that aren=
=E2=80=99t in the spirit of what (I intended) financially sustainable trave=
l to be. People confuse financially sustainable travel with a long term tra=
vel budget. While the two are intrinsically connected, they are not the sam=
e.&nbsp;</p>



<p><em>Is it related to environmental sustainability?</em> Nope.</p>



<p><em>Is it about budget travel?</em> Absolutely not! (Just look at some o=
f my <a href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo.com/category/financial-case=
-studies/" data-modified-href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo.com/catego=
ry/financial-case-studies">Financial Case Studies</a> to see people who are=
 traveling full-time with six-figure incomes, as well as others traveling o=
n a budget).</p>



<p>While the definition of financially sustainable travel seemed intuitive =
to me, perhaps it=E2=80=99s not to everybody. So, it=E2=80=99s time to get =
really clear:</p>



<p data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true"><strong>Financially sustainable trav=
el is about having (ie: saving or earning) sufficient money to pay for your=
 desired travel lifestyle (whatever that looks like). </strong></p>
