<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">How to Spend Less Than You Earn (Traveling o=
n a Budget)</h3>



<p>Here=E2=80=99s my big secret; it=E2=80=99s my secret to budgeting (at ho=
me or abroad), and to staying on track with expenses and thus to a financia=
lly sustainable travel lifestyle. Traveling on a budget doesn=E2=80=99t alw=
ays mean scrimping, but it does mean the following:</p>



<p><strong>I track every dollar/yen/euro/peso/whatever that I spend. Every.=
 Single. One. </strong></p>



<p>I do this day in, day out, rain or shine. No matter how small the expens=
e, it gets logged. No judgements or regrets=E2=80=A6I just log it.</p>



<p>This is made ridiculously easy by the Trail Wallet app, which is probabl=
y my all-time favourite and most useful travel app. <em>Ever.</em> (<em>See=
 also: </em><a href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo.com/best-travel-apps=
/" data-modified-href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo.com/best-travel-ap=
ps"><em>25 Must-Have Travel Apps</em></a><em>) </em></p>



<p data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true">I can track money in multiple curren=
cies, and it automatically converts it to US dollars. This way I can see wh=
at I=E2=80=99m spending each month, as I go. I can also track how much I=E2=
=80=99ve spent per country or trip. And I can export my data into a spreads=
heet so I can play with the numbers even more (which is what I use to formu=
late <a href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo.com/category/annual-expense=
-income-reviews/" data-modified-href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo.com=
/category/annual-expense-income-reviews">my annual expense reports</a>.</p>
