<p>I started out travelling full-time with a fixed income (from the sale of=
 my business) of $18,000/year =E2=80=93 which wasn=E2=80=99t even close to =
being enough to support me as I had been living in Toronto. I had no reason=
 to expect it would support me abroad.</p>



<p>But it did =E2=80=93 in spades. In those initial years, I lived (<em>and=
 lived very well</em>) in places where the cost of living was actually pret=
ty high. Hawaii. Australia. New Zealand. Western Europe. I made a go of it =
there, in ways I couldn=E2=80=99t have imagined possible when I started out=
 traveling.</p>



<p>Techniques like <a href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo.com/travel-ti=
ps-resources/get-free-accommodation-around-world/" data-modified-href=3D"ht=
tps://www.theprofessionalhobo.com/travel-tips-resources/get-free-accommodat=
ion-around-world">how to get free accommodation</a> and the creative use of=
 <a href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo.com/financial-travel-tip-84-bei=
ng-a-first-class-flyer/" data-modified-href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalh=
obo.com/financial-travel-tip-84-being-a-first-class-flyer">frequent flyer m=
iles</a> (to fly in business class for less than the price of a coach ticke=
t) kept my expenses not only in check, but <em>below</em> my small income. =
(Unfortunately, I don=E2=80=99t have expense reports for those years, as I =
didn=E2=80=99t start tracking and publishing that information until 2010).<=
/p>



<p data-slot-rendered-content=3D"true">As my income increased, so too did m=
y travel expenses. I no longer <em>had</em> to have free accommodation; I c=
ould afford a home base (which I enjoyed in various countries, including Au=
stralia, Grenada, Peru, and now, <a href=3D"https://www.theprofessionalhobo=
.com/my-epic-search-for-a-home-base/" data-modified-href=3D"https://www.the=
professionalhobo.com/my-epic-search-for-a-home-base">Toronto</a>). I could =
travel faster if I wanted to.</p>
